phil_data = pd.read_csv('/content/drive/MyDrive/5243/philosophy_data.csv')

The raw data is at https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/kouroshalizadeh/history-of-philosophy

I became interested in philosophy when I was in college. At the same time, I read some books on the history of philosophy and learned about the background and contributions of many famous philosophers. Among them, Aristotle and Plato impressed me the most. In this set of data, I was fortunate to see many famous quotes from them.

While looking at these famous philosophical quotes, I suddenly had an interesting thought: Who speaks the most philosophical quotes. I guess it should be Plato, because he started the famous Platonic school, and he can be regarded as one of the founders of philosophy.

Qustion1: who speaks the most¶

In [ ]:

I found out I was wrong. Aristotle is worthy of Plato's teacher. He has spoken more wise words than Plato. At the same time, it can be clearly seen that the famous quotes of Aristotle far surpassed all philosophers except Plato and Hegel, which is close to 50,000 sentences. This is really incredible.

Here we found that the top3 authors are Aristotle, Plato and Hegel. Another interesting question appeared: what are the most common words said by them? What words are they used to say?

Q2: What are the most common words said by Aristotle, Plato, and Hegel¶

Here, I first removed stopwords and plot wordclouds of their quotes. Then, in order to see more clearly about which words they said the most, I plot a bar plot for each philosopher.

In [ ]:
from wordcloud import WordCloud, STOPWORDS, ImageColorGenerator
In [ ]:
phil_data.tokenized_txt = phil_data.tokenized_txt.apply(lambda x: re.sub("[\[\],?']",'', x).split())
In [ ]:
words = []
for word in phil_data.tokenized_txt:
  words += word

word_counts = Counter(words).most_common(150)

type(word_counts)
word = []
count = []
stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)
for wordcount in word_counts:
  if wordcount[0] not in stopwords:
    word.append(wordcount[0])
    count.append(wordcount[1])

Q3: Who like to speak long sentance?¶

In [ ]:
long_sen = phil_data.groupby(by = ['author']).mean().drop(columns = ['original_publication_date','corpus_edition_date'])
long_sen = long_sen.sort_values(by = 'sentence_length',ascending = False)[:40]
long_sen.reset_index(inplace = True)
In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.barplot(x= long_sen['author'], y=long_sen['sentence_length'])
plt.xlabel("Author")
plt.ylabel("Average Sentance Length")
plt.title("Who said the longest sentance")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()
In [ ]:
from operator import index
authors = ['Hegel','Aristotle', 'Plato']
index_list = long_sen[long_sen['author'].isin(authors)].index.tolist()
print('Here are the ranks of Hegal, Aristotle, Plato',index_list)

Here are the ranks of Hegal, Aristotle, Plato [11, 17, 33]

Here we can see Hegel likes to speak long sentances than Aristotle and Plato. As for me, long philosphy sentances are usally more difficult to understand, especially when they contains a plenty of difficult words. Let's see whose sentances are the most diffcult to be understanded.

phil_data['readability_score'] = phil_data.sentence_lowered.apply(lambda x : textstat.flesch_reading_ease(x))
In [ ]:
score = phil_data.groupby(by = ['author']).mean().drop(columns = ['original_publication_date','corpus_edition_date'])
readability_score = score.sort_values('readability_score').reset_index()
readability_score[:3]
Out[ ]:
author sentence_length readability_score
0 Husserl 185.473703 35.869110
1 Kant 198.159400 38.872220
2 Keynes 196.654060 40.330868
In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.barplot(x= readability_score['author'], y=readability_score['readability_score'])
plt.xlabel("Author")
plt.ylabel("Average Readability Score")
plt.title("Readability")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()

Here, larger readability score means easier to read. So as we can see, the readability score rank for the 3 philosophers are Plato > Aristotle > Hegel. Plato's quotes are one of the most readable, and Hegel's are one of the most difficult to read.

Is there a relation between the average length and readability of the quotes?

In [ ]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
x = readability_score['author']
y1 = readability_score['sentence_length']
y2 = readability_score['readability_score']

# Create the bar plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,6))
ax.bar(x, y1, label='Sentence Length')
ax.bar(x, y2, bottom=y1, label='Readability Score')

# Add axis labels and legend
ax.set_xlabel('Author')
ax.set_ylabel('Value')
ax.legend()
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
# Show the plot
plt.show()

The barplot shows the average sentance length and readability score. It looks like there is a trend that larger average sentance length result in lower readability score(more difficult to read). To learn more about the relation between length and readability, a scatter plot may help.

In [ ]:
sns.regplot(x='sentence_length', y='readability_score', data=readability_score)
plt.xlabel('Sentence Length')
plt.ylabel('Readability Score')
plt.show()

Summary¶

In summary, longer sentance tends to be more difficult to read. For Aristotle, Plaoto, Hegel, who speak the most quotes, Plato's quotes are kind of easier to read, and they are also shorter than the other two philosophers. So, if you are interested in philosophy and want to start learning, Plats's quotes might be a good choice!
